Introduction
In the previous quest, you learned how to obtain a sandbox API key which we will be using in our API request to the Circle Payment API. In this quest, we will go through what the Circle Payment API is, how you can send a card payment to the Circle Payment API using a web application and the processes behind it. We will also go through how you can query the status of a card payment transaction. 
For queries on this quest,  join our Discord, head to the #circle-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Describe the functionalities of the Circle Payment API
  • Understand how card payment works in the Circle Payment API
  • Make a card payment using the payment API on the sandbox environment 
  • Retrieve the status of a card payment using the Circle Payment API

To successfully complete this quest, you will need to do the following: 
  1. Complete the quiz and submit it successfully! To pass, you will need to get 7 out of 8 questions correct!

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to Circle Payments API
The Circle Payment API allows you to collect payments from your end users via traditional methods such as debit cards, credit cards and bank accounts as well as crypto wallets. These transactions are conducted in USDC, a stablecoin which we have learned about in the first quest. The Circle Payment API is designed for any business or e-commerce in mind and has been processing millions of card payments since 2014.
Step 2: Installing Circle's Sample Web Application
Now that you know what the Circle Payment API is, we will proceed to make a card payment using the Circle Payment API with the 3D Secure Authentication. Before we go through how you can make a card payment using the Circle Payment API, we will first need to understand what 3D Secure Authentication is. If you have ever made an online payment with your credit or debit card, you will arrive at a page where you will be required to enter a One-Time password (OTP). That feature is known as 3D Secure Authentication. It is a fraud prevention safeguard designed to provide an extra layer of security for online or mobile payments.
To understand how card payment works with Circle Payment API, we will be using a sample web application provided by Circle. We first need to install several programs. 

The first program to install is Git. Git is a distributed version control system that is used to track changes in files. For this quest, we will be using Git to clone the repository of the web application to show how card payment works in the sandbox environment. Cloning in Git is basically downloading a local copy of that online repository onto your file system. To check if you have installed Git, you can run the following command in your terminal or command line.
git -v

If a version number is returned, then Git is installed. Otherwise, refer to these instructions to install Git on your device. Once you have installed Git, you can use the same command to check if the installation is complete.

The next program to install is Node.js which is needed to run the web application. You can check if you have already installed Node.js using the command.
node -v

If a version number is not returned, then you will need to install Node.js from here. Once you have installed Node.js, you can use the same command to check if the installation is complete.

The next program you will need to install is Yarn. Yarn is a Node.js package manager which is used to download the required libraries to run web applications. These libraries are not pre-installed in the repository because it would make the repository's overall file size too large and affect the download times. Usually, these libraries can range from a few megabytes (MB) to several gigabytes (GB). Therefore, the standard practice to store your Node.js application on the repository is to exclude any external libraries and then require the users who cloned the repository to download the required library using a Node.js package manager. This way, you can keep your repository small and compact. 

You can check if you have Yarn installed using the following command.
yarn --version

If it does not return a version number, then you can run the following command to install Yarn. The next command uses npm (Node Package Manager), which is another Node.js package manager automatically installed when installing Node.js. The reason why we are using Yarn is because this web application is set up to use Yarn.
npm install --global yarn

Now that you have installed the required programs, we will clone the needed repository to a local destination. To do so, open your terminal and navigate to your desired file location. In your desired file location in your terminal or command line, run the following command.
git clone https://github.com/circlefin/payments-sample-app.git

Once you have cloned the repository, change your directory to the directory you just cloned with the following command.
cd payments-sample-app

Next, you will need to create a .env file. This will contain the environment variables that will be loaded into the web application upon start up. An environment variable is a dynamic-named value that changes based on the environment chosen. We need the environment variable to hold the URL of the sandbox payment API as the web application will read the URL from here. By having multiple instances of these .env files, you can switch the URL according to where you want it to point to. But in our case, we will only need to create one .env file. The following command is used to create the .env file and configure the base URL for API calls.
echo BASE_URL=https://api-sandbox.circle.com > .env

After creating the .env file, install the required libraries using the following command.
yarn install

Once the libraries have been installed, you can start the web application server with this next command.
yarn dev

Troubleshooting: When running the yarn dev command, and this error is encountered: error:0308010C: digital envelope routines::unsupported, it likely means that the node version that you are using is more recent than what the web application was built with. Please head to this link for steps on how to downgrade your node version to v16.13.

When the web application server starts, you will see the following output on your terminal. You know that it is running when you read the line that says Listening on .



Once the web application server is running, you can access the web application via http://localhost:3011/ on your browser. Your page should look similar to the 'expected output'.
Expected output
Step 3: Making Card Payments in the Sandbox Environment
The next step is to insert the API key that you obtained in the third quest. In the event that you did not save your API key, you may generate a new API key in the Circle Sandbox. Firstly, click the settings icon in the top right hand corner. It will open the right side menu where you need to insert your API key in the Your API Key field.


After inserting the API key, you can make a card payment. Returning to the main page, click on Charge Flow.



You now have a payment form where you need to fill in the card information. Don't worry, you wont need to use your payment cards for this step. Instead, you can use one of the test cards provided by Circle. Simply click the PREFILL FORM button (refer to image above) and select one of the options, which will automatically fill in the card and user details. For the amount, we will enter 9.99. Click on "MAKE PAYMENT" to submit the form.



In the next page, you should see that the payment status is confirmed. You will need to copy your payment ID for the next step.

Troubleshooting: If you dont see the PREFILL FORM button, double check to make sure that this is the URL youre on - http://localhost:3011/flow/charge. In the event you receive a "code 401, Malformed authorization. Is the authorization type missing?" response, do check that your API key is correctly input in the "authorization" tab. Otherwise, delete the existing key and re-enter it. 


On the other hand, you can test out different amounts such as 5.01 and 5.07 to trigger different errors. You can read this table to learn which amounts will trigger specific response codes. 

With this, you have sent a card payment to the Circle Payment API using that sample web application. In the next step, we will go through how you can retrieve the status of your card payment from the Circle Payment API.
Step 4: Making an API Call
This step will guide you in retrieving the status and other information about card payment transactions. To do this, you will need to open Postman which you installed and used in the second quest. If you have not completed the quest or do not have Postman installed, please refer to Quest 2 Step 5. 
On your Postman, reuse the Exchange API Rate collection to create our API request. On your Exchange API Rate collection folder, click the three dots icon on the right and that will produce a dropdown menu. From the dropdown menu, click on Add Request which will create a new request for you. 



In the new request tab, you will need to set the API key for the request. Firstly, in the authorization tab click on the dropdown box beside the Type text. In that dropdown menu, select Bearer Token. In the Token field, enter your API key that you obtained from the third quest.



Next to "GET", enter the following request URL for Postman to call: https://api-sandbox.circle.com/v1/payments/${PAYMENT_ID}
Replace ${PAYMENT_ID} with the payment ID that you copied in the previous step.

Next, perform the API call by clicking the Send button on the right.

Once you have sent the API call, you should receive a response that is similar to the image in 'expected output'. In the event your status says 'confirmed', click on the "Send" button once more. 

From this response, you can see that the payment status is paid. This means that the payment has been confirmed and the money has been transferred. You can also see that it provides details of the transaction such as the amount, fees involved, timestamps, verification status as well as any metadata provided during the API call.

Troubleshooting: If you receive a network error when sending your request, it could be due to the Circle API being blocked in your country. You may seek out solutions in the Discord #circle-helpdesk channel.

Important: Take a full screenshot of your Postman interface as that will be part of your submission. More details in Step 6.

Step 5: End-to-end Explanation of Payment Flows
In the previous step, we learned how you can perform an API call to the Circle Payment API to get information for your card payment. In this step, we will go through the process that the web application underwent when making a card payment. The image below shows the process of making a card payment using the web application. To avoid any confusion, the Merchant Server refers to the Node.js that is hosting the web application. 


Stage 1 of the process occurs when you open the URL on your browser and the page loads OpenPgP.js, a JavaScript library that is used for encryption. The reason why we need to encrypt the data that we send is because credit card details are sensitive data that can be easily misused and requests that you send to the Circle Payment API can be intercepted.

Stage 2 of the process is to get the public key for encryption from the Circle API. In cryptography, the study of techniques and practices to secure communication, encryption works with 2 keys one private key and one public key. The public key is used to encrypt the data into a ciphertext but cannot be used for decryption, which is why the Circle API is able to share its public key. The private key is used to decrypt the ciphertext back to its original form and Circle API uses this to decrypt any incoming data. The private key is not shared with any system outside the Circle API. 



Stage 3 of the process occurs when clicking the Make Payment button. At this stage, it will encrypt the necessary data using the public key obtained in Stage 2 and craft the request that will be sent to the Circle API. Besides the encrypted card details, the billing information, the session ID and the IP address of the user is also added to the request.

Stage 4 of the process is to send the request to the Merchant Server which will then be sent to the Circle API.

Stage 5 of the process is the sending of the request from the Merchant Server to the Circle API where it will collect the response and send it back to the browser. The response will contain the unique ID that is attached to the card details that was sent and can be used for the payment endpoint in the later stages. Part of the response would be the results of the different verification checks under the verification property. The 2 forms of verification are the Card Verification Value (CVV) and the Address Verification Service (AVS). CVV is a number that is printed on a payment card that is private to the card owner and is used to verify the card in question. AVS is a mechanism where it compares the provided billing address against the billing address provided by the card issuer. 

Stage 6 is triggered when it receives a successful response from the Circle API and the payment request is created. It will use the ID from the response in Stage 5 as the source of payment and it will add in the amount taken from the form and currency which in this case is by default USD. The refId property is added for idempotent requests. The session ID and the IP address needs to be included as they are used for preventing fraud. When creating a payment request, you can choose to authorize a payment only or authorize and capture the payment at the same time. Authorization is the action to check if the cardholder has sufficient funds/credit to cover the cost of the transaction while capture is the request for the transfer of funds from the card issuer. 

Stages 7 & 8 are the sending of the request from the browser to the Circle API. Once the request is processed, it will return the ID of the payment transaction as well as other information. The status of the transaction at this point is pending.

In Stage 9 after getting the response from Circle API, it will periodically poll the API until the status changes from pending to either confirmed or failed. The act of polling in a web application is the calling of the Circle API for the payment status at regular intervals until it changes from pending. The Circle API endpoint that was called is the same endpoint that we used in Step 4.

With this we have gone through the different stages of the process of creating a card payment request for the Circle Payment API.
